^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, a couple of comments. First, I believe that you should open all 15-17 balanced hands 1N, even with a 5 card major. That is why I opened my hand 1N. Some may argue 2H is a better contract, but I would say both contracts are about the same, and they both should go down with perfect defense.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Elizabeth's diamond lead was a good choice. The question is, is the 3 or the 8 correct. Some would argue the 8 because the 3 might imply an honor. Others would argue that the 8 implies less than 4 diamonds, top of nothing. There is no universal agreement.  I would tend to lead the 3 but that is just style.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, given Elizabeth lead the 8, Vered should realize South has the Jack. Therefore she should play a different suit after winning the trick. If she knew that Elizabeth had 4, she could play the King pinning the Jack, but she has no way of knowing that. So a spade switch is probably right, or even the Queen of hearts. A low diamond will always give away a trick.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


