UP|52|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First of all, as all of you know, I am a big believer in aggressive bidding. However, I think Elizabeth was somewhat too aggressive even for me by bidding 2S. She is at unfavorable vulnerability, she only has 5 spades, and they are not very good.  I think a strategic pass is best. One other point on the auction. Most people these days play 2C over 1D is a game force, if they play 2 over 1. |
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I do not. And this hand is a good example why 2C is a much more natural bid than 1N over 1D. Here is my reasoning as to why I do not think 2C should be a game force, although I am in the minority. With one of a major, you have the forcing NT for those hands when you have 10 or 11 points. |
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But over 1D the forcing NT does not apply. so I don't think 2C should be a game force, because you have no good way of showing a hand such as Eddy's hand. However, as I said, that is a minority opinion these days, just my two cents for what it is worth.|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play. The club play is an interesting problem. If Vered has the King, then Elizabeth made a nice play and she was rather unlucky that the King was offside and Vered had a singleton. So, I think the club play was correct in general, even though it did not work on this hand. Eddy made a very nice switch to the King of spades and partner should have honored that switch. Once she ruffs the club, she should play the nine of spades to take the last spade off dummy.|
PG| ***** 36 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Then Eddy gets to cash 2 more club tricks. As a result, not playing a spade cost their side 2 or 3 tricks. Since Eddy played the King, he must have the Queen so the spade is very safe. One other comment about leading the Ace of hearts from A K combination. I know on opening lead, you lead Ace from AK. However, in the middle of the hand, I recommend King from AK. Once that wins, partner knows you have the Ace.|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Whereas if you lead the A, partner is not sure who has the King. Eddy asked about Vered playing another diamond. Vered knows both Eddy and Elizabeth are out, so another diamond is not a good play. A spade is best, for the reasons stated.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


