UP|52|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, there was again lots to talk about the play. We discussed the bidding, and why I never mentioned my hearts. As to the play, let's first look at the opening lead.  Vered has a tough lead. However, on this hand, it is clear Elizabeth has clubs. So, a club is probably not a good lead. She opened 1C and bid 1NT over 1D, denying a 4 card major. Therefore, she has to have at least 4 clubs, because the only reason she would have 3 clubs is if she had a 4 card major.|
PG| ***** 74 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*Bnome: ^*N|cp||at|Howard has an excellent lesson on "Counting Defenders Distributions" which you can find at his web site ^*Hwww.bridgesights.com/hondobridge/##declarer^*N in the "Declarer Play Lessons" section. The BBO movie is awesome! I cannot help not plugging my work too!!|
PG| ***** 75 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As a general rule, 85% of the time when someone opens better minor, they have a 4 card suit at least. So, you should assume if someone opens 1C or 1D, they probably have at least 4 in the suit. Therefore, I would probably lead a heart, which doesn't hurt and doesn't help,  partner  has 4 hearts and the honors will help set up the suit. On this hand it is neutral as it turns out. If South had not bid diamonds, I would lead a diamond, but since he did bid diamonds I think a major is called for.|
PG| ***** 76 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, once a club is led, Elizabeth needs to count her tricks. She has eight sure tricks and needs to develop one more trick. Personally I would try to develop a diamond trick, as there are lots of combinations where you get a diamond. To get an extra hearts trick you need a 3-3 break. Whereas a diamond depends on basically the A, Q, or 10 being doubleton or a 3-3 break. So, at trick 2 I lead a low diamond which works well any time Eddy has the Queen and that is my ninth trick as is turns out. |
PG| ***** 77 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Elizabeth sort of tried 2 things at once, and hence, should have gone down. First she tried hearts, and then switched to diamonds. Then, Eddy made a nice spade play. However, at trick nine, he then forgot to take the setting trick when Elizabeth led a 2nd diamond off dummy. |
PG| ***** 78 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|At that point his side has taken 3 tricks, and the Queen of diamonds and Queen of spades are both good. So, Eddy should take the Queen of diamonds and cash the Q of spades. Remember "It is never wrong to beat the contract." |
