^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I had a lot of questions about the bidding here. Let me first discuss responses when partner opens 2C. Most people play 2D as "waiting", meaning it basically is almost an automatic response to 2C. The reason that is popular is that it takes up the least amount of bidding room, and allows the 2C opener a lot of room to describe her hand. |
PG| ***** 122 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Some people play that 2D promises at least one Ace or King, and that 2H shows a "bust" hand, no Aces or Kings. Other people, me included play "2nd negative", with a bust hand you bid 2D and then bid your cheapest minor to show a bust hand. So, the auction for example of 2C-2D-2H-3C, shows that responder has a bust hand if you play 2nd negative.|
PG| ***** 123 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Another approach some people use is steps where responses to 2C either shows points ( 2D shows 1-3, 2H shows 4-6 points, etc) or controls (2D shows no more than 1 King, 2H shows 2 Kings or 1 Ace, 2S shows an Ace and a King, and 2N shows 3 Kings. I do not like step responses personally. They take up extra bidding room and often wrong side the contract.|
PG| ***** 124 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I prefer bidding 2D over 2C most of the time because that gives the 2C openers the most room to describe their hand. One other comment on the bidding on this hand. Patti should strongly consider 3N over my 3C bid. Even with a void, 3N is often the best contract. 9 tricks are often easier than 10.|
PG| ***** 125 ***** |


NT|^B@2
robzim: Even without transportation?|
