However, we all were taught to avoid playing 5 of a minor. I'm confident that your experience since then has reinforced that. Should you really throw all that out the window when your RHO preempts? |
PG| ***** 161 ***** |


AT|

Good news! There is a solution. When partner opens and your RHO jumps to 3D, 3H, or 3S, I define double as a hand with 10+ HCP that is looking for 3NT. If the doubler had a stopper he would have bid 3NT. Therefore, his double denies a stopper in the opponent's suit. If you delete the six letters in the middle of the phrase "THRee notrUMP", the result is "THRUMP". Therefore, these doubles are referred to as Thrump Doubles. |
PG| ***** 162 ***** |


AT|

Ever since I first defined a double of 3@D, 3@H or 3@S after partner opens as a Thrump Double, they have proved to be invaluable in getting to 3NT. In fact, unless your opponents agree to stop preempting, or you become enamored of playing in 5 of a minor, I would not want to play bridge without THRUMP Doubles. |
